Note:
math/symbolic/functions.runa
Symbolic Mathematical Functions and Special Function Library

This module provides comprehensive symbolic special function operations including:
- Elementary functions (exponential, logarithmic, trigonometric)
- Hyperbolic functions and their inverses
- Special functions (Gamma, Beta, Error functions)
- Orthogonal polynomials (Legendre, Chebyshev, Hermite, Laguerre)
- Bessel functions and modified Bessel functions
- Hypergeometric functions and confluent forms
- Elliptic functions and elliptic integrals
- Zeta function and related number theory functions
- Statistical distribution functions
- Combinatorial functions and generating functions
- Asymptotic expansions of special functions
- Functional equations and transformation formulas
- Series representations and continued fractions
- Symbolic function composition and inversion
- Special function identities and relationships
:End Note

Import "dev/debug/errors/core" as Errors
Import "math/symbolic/core" as SymbolicCore
Import "math/symbolic/algebra" as Algebra
Import "text/string/manipulation" as StringOps
Import "text/string/core" as StringCore
Import "data/collections/core/list" as ListOps
Import "data/collections/core/map" as Map
Import "data/collections/core/dictionary" as Dictionary
Import "text/parsing/expression_parser" as Parser
Import "math/core/constants" as Constants

Note: =====================================================================
Note: FUNCTION DATA STRUCTURES
Note: =====================================================================

Type called "SpecialFunction":
    function_name as String
    parameters as List[String]
    function_type as String
    domain as Dictionary[String, String]
    range as Dictionary[String, String]
    series_representation as String
    asymptotic_form as String
    special_values as Dictionary[String, String]

Type called "OrthogonalPolynomial":
    polynomial_family as String
    degree as Integer
    weight_function as String
    orthogonality_interval as Dictionary[String, String]
    normalization_constant as String
    recurrence_relation as Dictionary[String, String]
    generating_function as String

Type called "EllipticFunction":
    function_type as String
    modulus as String
    parameter as String
    periods as Dictionary[String, String]
    invariants as Dictionary[String, String]
    discriminant as String

Type called "HypergeometricFunction":
    function_type as String
    numerator_parameters as List[String]
    denominator_parameters as List[String]
    argument as String
    convergence_radius as String
    transformation_formulas as List[String]

Type called "FunctionSeries":
    function_name as String
    expansion_point as String
    series_type as String
    coefficients as Dictionary[String, String]
    convergence_properties as Dictionary[String, String]

Note: =====================================================================
Note: ELEMENTARY FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "symbolic_exponential" that takes argument as String, base as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic exponential function with arbitrary base
    Note: Handle special cases and simplifications
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "1" and base equals "e":
        Return "e"
    
    If base equals "e":
        If argument equals "ln(x)":
            Return "x"
        If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "ln("):
            Let inner_expr be StringCore.substring(argument, 3, StringCore.length(argument) - 1)
            Return inner_expr
        Return "exp(" + argument + ")"
    
    If base equals "10":
        Return "10^(" + argument + ")"
    
    If base equals "2":
        If argument equals "log_2(x)":
            Return "x"
        Return "2^(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case - arbitrary base
    Return base + "^(" + argument + ")"

Process called "symbolic_logarithm" that takes argument as String, base as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic logarithm with arbitrary base and branch cuts
    Note: Handle special cases and identities
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals base:
        Return "1"
    
    If base equals "e":
        If argument equals "e":
            Return "1"
        If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "exp("):
            Let inner_expr be StringCore.substring(argument, 4, StringCore.length(argument) - 1)
            Return inner_expr
        If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "e^"):
            Let exponent be StringCore.substring(argument, 2, StringCore.length(argument))
            Return exponent
        Return "ln(" + argument + ")"
    
    If base equals "10":
        If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "10^"):
            Let exponent be StringCore.substring(argument, 3, StringCore.length(argument))
            Return exponent
        Return "log(" + argument + ")"
    
    If base equals "2":
        If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "2^"):
            Let exponent be StringCore.substring(argument, 2, StringCore.length(argument))
            Return exponent
        Return "log_2(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case using change of base formula
    Return "ln(" + argument + ")/ln(" + base + ")"

Process called "symbolic_power" that takes base as String, exponent as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic power function with complex exponents
    Note: Handle special cases and power rules
    If exponent equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If exponent equals "1":
        Return base
    
    If base equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If base equals "1":
        Return "1"
    
    If base equals "e" and exponent equals "1":
        Return "e"
    
    Note: Handle negative exponents
    If StringCore.starts_with(exponent, "-"):
        Let positive_exp be StringCore.substring(exponent, 1, StringCore.length(exponent))
        Return "1/(" + base + "^" + positive_exp + ")"
    
    Note: Handle fractional exponents (roots)
    If StringCore.contains(exponent, "1/"):
        Let root_index be StringCore.substring(exponent, 2, StringCore.length(exponent))
        Return root_index + "√(" + base + ")"
    
    Note: Handle specific numerical exponents
    If exponent equals "2":
        Return base + "²"
    
    If exponent equals "3":
        Return base + "³"
    
    Note: General case
    Return base + "^(" + exponent + ")"

Process called "symbolic_root" that takes argument as String, root_index as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic nth root with principal value
    Note: Handle special cases and root simplifications
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "1"
    
    If root_index equals "1":
        Return argument
    
    If root_index equals "2":
        If argument equals "4":
            Return "2"
        If argument equals "9":
            Return "3"
        If argument equals "16":
            Return "4"
        If argument equals "25":
            Return "5"
        If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "x²") or StringCore.ends_with(argument, "²"):
            Let base_var be StringCore.replace(argument, "²", "")
            Return "|" + base_var + "|"
        Return "√(" + argument + ")"
    
    If root_index equals "3":
        If argument equals "8":
            Return "2"
        If argument equals "27":
            Return "3"
        If argument equals "64":
            Return "4"
        Return "∛(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Handle perfect powers
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "^"):
        Let power_parts be StringCore.split(argument, "^")
        If ListOps.length(power_parts) equals 2:
            Let base be ListOps.get(power_parts, 0)
            Let exponent be ListOps.get(power_parts, 1)
            Return base + "^(" + exponent + "/" + root_index + ")"
    
    Note: General case - nth root
    Return root_index + "√(" + argument + ")"

Process called "complex_exponential" that takes complex_argument as String returns String:
    Note: Complex exponential function e^(a+bi)
    Note: Use Euler's formula: e^(a+bi) = e^a * (cos(b) + i*sin(b))
    If StringCore.contains(complex_argument, "+") and StringCore.contains(complex_argument, "i"):
        Let parts be StringCore.split(complex_argument, "+")
        If ListOps.length(parts) equals 2:
            Let real_part be ListOps.get(parts, 0)
            Let imaginary_part be StringCore.replace(ListOps.get(parts, 1), "i", "")
            Return "exp(" + real_part + ") * (cos(" + imaginary_part + ") + i*sin(" + imaginary_part + "))"
    
    If StringCore.contains(complex_argument, "-") and StringCore.contains(complex_argument, "i"):
        Let parts be StringCore.split(complex_argument, "-")
        If ListOps.length(parts) equals 2:
            Let real_part be ListOps.get(parts, 0)
            Let imaginary_part be StringCore.replace(ListOps.get(parts, 1), "i", "")
            Return "exp(" + real_part + ") * (cos(" + imaginary_part + ") - i*sin(" + imaginary_part + "))"
    
    Note: Pure imaginary case
    If StringCore.starts_with(complex_argument, "i") or StringCore.ends_with(complex_argument, "i"):
        Let imaginary_part be StringCore.replace(complex_argument, "i", "")
        Return "cos(" + imaginary_part + ") + i*sin(" + imaginary_part + ")"
    
    Note: Real case
    Return "exp(" + complex_argument + ")"

Process called "complex_logarithm" that takes complex_argument as String, branch as String returns String:
    Note: Complex logarithm with specified branch
    Note: Use formula: log(z) = log|z| + i*arg(z) + 2πik for branch k
    If complex_argument equals "1":
        Return "0"
    
    If complex_argument equals "-1":
        If branch equals "principal":
            Return "iπ"
        Otherwise:
            Return "iπ + 2πi*" + branch
    
    If complex_argument equals "i":
        If branch equals "principal":
            Return "iπ/2"
        Otherwise:
            Return "iπ/2 + 2πi*" + branch
    
    If complex_argument equals "-i":
        If branch equals "principal":
            Return "-iπ/2"
        Otherwise:
            Return "-iπ/2 + 2πi*" + branch
    
    Note: General complex form a+bi
    If StringCore.contains(complex_argument, "+") and StringCore.contains(complex_argument, "i"):
        Let parts be StringCore.split(complex_argument, "+")
        If ListOps.length(parts) equals 2:
            Let a be ListOps.get(parts, 0)
            Let b be StringCore.replace(ListOps.get(parts, 1), "i", "")
            If branch equals "principal":
                Return "ln(√(" + a + "² + " + b + "²)) + i*arctan(" + b + "/" + a + ")"
            Otherwise:
                Return "ln(√(" + a + "² + " + b + "²)) + i*(arctan(" + b + "/" + a + ") + 2π*" + branch + ")"
    
    Note: Real argument
    If branch equals "principal":
        Return "ln(" + complex_argument + ")"
    Otherwise:
        Return "ln(" + complex_argument + ") + 2πi*" + branch

Note: =====================================================================
Note: TRIGONOMETRIC FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "symbolic_sine" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic sine function with exact values at special points
    Note: Handle special angle values and identities
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "π/6" or argument equals "30°":
        Return "1/2"
    
    If argument equals "π/4" or argument equals "45°":
        Return "√2/2"
    
    If argument equals "π/3" or argument equals "60°":
        Return "√3/2"
    
    If argument equals "π/2" or argument equals "90°":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "π" or argument equals "180°":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "3π/2" or argument equals "270°":
        Return "-1"
    
    If argument equals "2π" or argument equals "360°":
        Return "0"
    
    Note: Handle negative angles - sin(-x) = -sin(x)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return "-" + symbolic_sine(positive_arg)
    
    Note: Handle multiple of π
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "π"):
        If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "2π"):
            Return "0"
        If StringCore.contains(argument, "+"):
            Return "sin(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "sin(" + argument + ")"

Process called "symbolic_cosine" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic cosine function with exact values
    Note: Handle special angle values and identities
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "π/6" or argument equals "30°":
        Return "√3/2"
    
    If argument equals "π/4" or argument equals "45°":
        Return "√2/2"
    
    If argument equals "π/3" or argument equals "60°":
        Return "1/2"
    
    If argument equals "π/2" or argument equals "90°":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "π" or argument equals "180°":
        Return "-1"
    
    If argument equals "3π/2" or argument equals "270°":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "2π" or argument equals "360°":
        Return "1"
    
    Note: Handle negative angles - cos(-x) = cos(x) (even function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return symbolic_cosine(positive_arg)
    
    Note: Handle multiple of π
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "π"):
        If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "2π"):
            Return "1"
        If StringCore.contains(argument, "+"):
            Return "cos(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "cos(" + argument + ")"

Process called "symbolic_tangent" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic tangent function with singularity handling
    Note: Handle special angle values and singularities
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "π/6" or argument equals "30°":
        Return "1/√3"
    
    If argument equals "π/4" or argument equals "45°":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "π/3" or argument equals "60°":
        Return "√3"
    
    If argument equals "π" or argument equals "180°":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "2π" or argument equals "360°":
        Return "0"
    
    Note: Check for singularities (where cosine = 0)
    If argument equals "π/2" or argument equals "90°":
        Return "∞"
    
    If argument equals "3π/2" or argument equals "270°":
        Return "∞"
    
    Note: Handle negative angles - tan(-x) = -tan(x) (odd function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Let positive_result be symbolic_tangent(positive_arg)
        If positive_result equals "∞":
            Return "-∞"
        Return "-" + positive_result
    
    Note: Handle expressions involving π
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "π"):
        If StringCore.contains(argument, "π/2"):
            Return "∞"
        If StringCore.contains(argument, "+"):
            Return "tan(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "tan(" + argument + ")"

Process called "inverse_trigonometric" that takes function_name as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Inverse trigonometric functions (arcsin, arccos, arctan)
    Note: Handle different inverse trig functions with special values
    If function_name equals "arcsin" or function_name equals "asin":
        If argument equals "0":
            Return "0"
        If argument equals "1/2":
            Return "π/6"
        If argument equals "√2/2":
            Return "π/4"
        If argument equals "√3/2":
            Return "π/3"
        If argument equals "1":
            Return "π/2"
        If argument equals "-1":
            Return "-π/2"
        Return "arcsin(" + argument + ")"
    
    If function_name equals "arccos" or function_name equals "acos":
        If argument equals "1":
            Return "0"
        If argument equals "√3/2":
            Return "π/6"
        If argument equals "√2/2":
            Return "π/4"
        If argument equals "1/2":
            Return "π/3"
        If argument equals "0":
            Return "π/2"
        If argument equals "-1":
            Return "π"
        Return "arccos(" + argument + ")"
    
    If function_name equals "arctan" or function_name equals "atan":
        If argument equals "0":
            Return "0"
        If argument equals "1/√3":
            Return "π/6"
        If argument equals "1":
            Return "π/4"
        If argument equals "√3":
            Return "π/3"
        Return "arctan(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Unknown function name
    Return function_name + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "trigonometric_identities" that takes expression as String, identity_type as String returns String:
    Note: Apply trigonometric identities to simplify expressions
    Note: Handle common trigonometric identities
    If identity_type equals "pythagorean":
        If expression equals "sin²(x) + cos²(x)":
            Return "1"
        If expression equals "1 - sin²(x)":
            Return "cos²(x)"
        If expression equals "1 - cos²(x)":
            Return "sin²(x)"
        If expression equals "sec²(x) - 1":
            Return "tan²(x)"
        If expression equals "csc²(x) - 1":
            Return "cot²(x)"
    
    If identity_type equals "double_angle":
        If expression equals "sin(2x)":
            Return "2*sin(x)*cos(x)"
        If expression equals "cos(2x)":
            Return "cos²(x) - sin²(x)"
        If expression equals "tan(2x)":
            Return "2*tan(x)/(1 - tan²(x))"
    
    If identity_type equals "half_angle":
        If expression equals "sin(x/2)":
            Return "±√((1 - cos(x))/2)"
        If expression equals "cos(x/2)":
            Return "±√((1 + cos(x))/2)"
        If expression equals "tan(x/2)":
            Return "sin(x)/(1 + cos(x))"
    
    If identity_type equals "sum_to_product":
        If StringCore.contains(expression, "sin(A) + sin(B)"):
            Return "2*sin((A+B)/2)*cos((A-B)/2)"
        If StringCore.contains(expression, "cos(A) + cos(B)"):
            Return "2*cos((A+B)/2)*cos((A-B)/2)"
    
    If identity_type equals "product_to_sum":
        If StringCore.contains(expression, "sin(A)*cos(B)"):
            Return "(sin(A+B) + sin(A-B))/2"
        If StringCore.contains(expression, "cos(A)*cos(B)"):
            Return "(cos(A+B) + cos(A-B))/2"
    
    Note: No applicable identity found
    Return expression

Note: =====================================================================
Note: HYPERBOLIC FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "symbolic_sinh" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic hyperbolic sine function
    Note: Handle special values and identities for hyperbolic sine
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "ln(2)":
        Return "3/4"
    
    Note: Handle negative arguments - sinh(-x) = -sinh(x) (odd function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return "-" + symbolic_sinh(positive_arg)
    
    Note: Use exponential definition: sinh(x) = (e^x - e^(-x))/2
    If argument equals "x":
        Return "(exp(x) - exp(-x))/2"
    
    Note: Handle inverse relationships
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "asinh("):
        Let inner_expr be StringCore.substring(argument, 6, StringCore.length(argument) - 1)
        Return inner_expr
    
    Note: Handle multiples and expressions
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "*"):
        Return "sinh(" + argument + ")"
    
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "+") or StringCore.contains(argument, "-"):
        Return "sinh(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "sinh(" + argument + ")"

Process called "symbolic_cosh" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic hyperbolic cosine function
    Note: Handle special values and identities for hyperbolic cosine
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "ln(2)":
        Return "5/4"
    
    Note: Handle negative arguments - cosh(-x) = cosh(x) (even function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return symbolic_cosh(positive_arg)
    
    Note: Use exponential definition: cosh(x) = (e^x + e^(-x))/2
    If argument equals "x":
        Return "(exp(x) + exp(-x))/2"
    
    Note: Handle inverse relationships
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "acosh("):
        Let inner_expr be StringCore.substring(argument, 6, StringCore.length(argument) - 1)
        Return inner_expr
    
    Note: Handle multiples and expressions
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "*"):
        Return "cosh(" + argument + ")"
    
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "+") or StringCore.contains(argument, "-"):
        Return "cosh(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "cosh(" + argument + ")"

Process called "symbolic_tanh" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Symbolic hyperbolic tangent function
    Note: Handle special values and identities for hyperbolic tangent
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "ln(2)":
        Return "3/5"
    
    Note: Handle negative arguments - tanh(-x) = -tanh(x) (odd function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return "-" + symbolic_tanh(positive_arg)
    
    Note: Use exponential definition: tanh(x) = (e^x - e^(-x))/(e^x + e^(-x))
    If argument equals "x":
        Return "(exp(x) - exp(-x))/(exp(x) + exp(-x))"
    
    Note: Handle inverse relationships
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "atanh("):
        Let inner_expr be StringCore.substring(argument, 6, StringCore.length(argument) - 1)
        Return inner_expr
    
    Note: Handle limits - tanh approaches ±1 as x approaches ±∞
    If argument equals "∞":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "-∞":
        Return "-1"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "tanh(" + argument + ")"

Process called "inverse_hyperbolic" that takes function_name as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Inverse hyperbolic functions (asinh, acosh, atanh)
    Note: Handle different inverse hyperbolic functions
    If function_name equals "asinh" or function_name equals "sinh^-1":
        If argument equals "0":
            Return "0"
        Note: Use logarithmic definition: asinh(x) = ln(x + √(x² + 1))
        If argument equals "x":
            Return "ln(x + √(x² + 1))"
        Return "asinh(" + argument + ")"
    
    If function_name equals "acosh" or function_name equals "cosh^-1":
        If argument equals "1":
            Return "0"
        Note: Use logarithmic definition: acosh(x) = ln(x + √(x² - 1))
        If argument equals "x":
            Return "ln(x + √(x² - 1))"
        Return "acosh(" + argument + ")"
    
    If function_name equals "atanh" or function_name equals "tanh^-1":
        If argument equals "0":
            Return "0"
        Note: Use logarithmic definition: atanh(x) = (1/2)ln((1+x)/(1-x))
        If argument equals "x":
            Return "(1/2)*ln((1+x)/(1-x))"
        Return "atanh(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Unknown function name
    Return function_name + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "hyperbolic_identities" that takes expression as String returns String:
    Note: Apply hyperbolic identities for simplification
    Note: Handle common hyperbolic identities
    If expression equals "cosh²(x) - sinh²(x)":
        Return "1"
    
    If expression equals "1 - tanh²(x)":
        Return "sech²(x)"
    
    If expression equals "coth²(x) - 1":
        Return "csch²(x)"
    
    Note: Addition formulas
    If StringCore.contains(expression, "sinh(A+B)"):
        Return "sinh(A)*cosh(B) + cosh(A)*sinh(B)"
    
    If StringCore.contains(expression, "cosh(A+B)"):
        Return "cosh(A)*cosh(B) + sinh(A)*sinh(B)"
    
    If StringCore.contains(expression, "tanh(A+B)"):
        Return "(tanh(A) + tanh(B))/(1 + tanh(A)*tanh(B))"
    
    Note: Double angle formulas
    If expression equals "sinh(2x)":
        Return "2*sinh(x)*cosh(x)"
    
    If expression equals "cosh(2x)":
        Return "cosh²(x) + sinh²(x)"
    
    If expression equals "tanh(2x)":
        Return "2*tanh(x)/(1 + tanh²(x))"
    
    Note: Half angle formulas
    If expression equals "sinh(x/2)":
        Return "±√((cosh(x) - 1)/2)"
    
    If expression equals "cosh(x/2)":
        Return "√((cosh(x) + 1)/2)"
    
    If expression equals "tanh(x/2)":
        Return "sinh(x)/(1 + cosh(x))"
    
    Note: No applicable identity found
    Return expression

Note: =====================================================================
Note: GAMMA AND BETA FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "gamma_function" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Gamma function Γ(z) with complex argument
    Note: Handle special values and identities for gamma function
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "2":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "3":
        Return "2"
    
    If argument equals "4":
        Return "6"
    
    If argument equals "5":
        Return "24"
    
    Note: Gamma function for positive integers: Γ(n) = (n-1)!
    If argument equals "n":
        Return "(n-1)!"
    
    Note: Special fractional values
    If argument equals "1/2":
        Return "√π"
    
    If argument equals "3/2":
        Return "√π/2"
    
    If argument equals "5/2":
        Return "3√π/4"
    
    Note: Handle negative arguments using reflection formula
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return "π/(sin(π*" + positive_arg + ") * Γ(" + positive_arg + "))"
    
    Note: Recurrence relation: Γ(z+1) = z*Γ(z)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "+1"):
        Let base_arg be StringCore.replace(argument, "+1", "")
        Return base_arg + " * Γ(" + base_arg + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "Γ(" + argument + ")"

Process called "log_gamma_function" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Logarithm of gamma function for numerical stability
    Note: Handle special values and use properties of log gamma
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "2":
        Return "0"
    
    Note: For positive integers: ln(Γ(n)) = ln((n-1)!)
    If argument equals "3":
        Return "ln(2)"
    
    If argument equals "4":
        Return "ln(6)"
    
    If argument equals "5":
        Return "ln(24)"
    
    Note: Special fractional values
    If argument equals "1/2":
        Return "ln(√π) = ln(π)/2"
    
    If argument equals "3/2":
        Return "ln(√π/2) = ln(π)/2 - ln(2)"
    
    Note: Use recurrence relation: ln(Γ(z+1)) = ln(z) + ln(Γ(z))
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "+1"):
        Let base_arg be StringCore.replace(argument, "+1", "")
        Return "ln(" + base_arg + ") + ln(Γ(" + base_arg + "))"
    
    Note: Handle large arguments using Stirling's approximation
    If argument equals "n" and StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        Return "n*ln(n) - n + ln(2π*n)/2"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "ln(Γ(" + argument + "))"

Process called "beta_function" that takes argument_a as String, argument_b as String returns String:
    Note: Beta function B(a,b) = Γ(a)Γ(b)/Γ(a+b)
    Note: Handle special values and use gamma function relationship
    If argument_a equals "1" and argument_b equals "1":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument_a equals "1":
        Return "1/" + argument_b
    
    If argument_b equals "1":
        Return "1/" + argument_a
    
    Note: Symmetry property: B(a,b) = B(b,a)
    If argument_a equals argument_b:
        Return "B(" + argument_a + "," + argument_a + ")"
    
    Note: Special integer values
    If argument_a equals "2" and argument_b equals "2":
        Return "1/6"
    
    If argument_a equals "1/2" and argument_b equals "1/2":
        Return "π"
    
    Note: Use relationship with gamma function: B(a,b) = Γ(a)Γ(b)/Γ(a+b)
    Let sum_args be argument_a + "+" + argument_b
    Return "Γ(" + argument_a + ")*Γ(" + argument_b + ")/Γ(" + sum_args + ")"

Process called "incomplete_gamma" that takes s as String, x as String returns String:
    Note: Incomplete gamma function γ(s,x)
    Note: Handle special cases and use series representation
    If x equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If x equals "∞":
        Return "Γ(" + s + ")"
    
    If s equals "1":
        Return "1 - exp(-" + x + ")"
    
    If s equals "1/2":
        Return "√π * erf(√" + x + ")"
    
    Note: For positive integer s, use recursive relation
    If s equals "n" and StringCore.contains(s, "integer"):
        Return "(n-1)! * (1 - exp(-" + x + ") * Σ(" + x + "^k/k!))"  
    
    Note: Series representation: γ(s,x) = x^s * exp(-x) * Σ(x^n/Γ(s+n+1))
    Return "γ(" + s + "," + x + ")"

Process called "incomplete_beta" that takes a as String, b as String, x as String returns String:
    Note: Incomplete beta function I_x(a,b)
    Note: Handle special cases and boundary conditions
    If x equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If x equals "1":
        Return "1"
    
    Note: Special case when a = 1
    If a equals "1":
        Return "1 - (1-" + x + ")^" + b
    
    Note: Special case when b = 1
    If b equals "1":
        Return x + "^" + a
    
    Note: Symmetry relation: I_x(a,b) = 1 - I_(1-x)(b,a)
    If StringCore.contains(x, "1-"):
        Let complement_x be StringCore.replace(x, "1-", "")
        Return "1 - I_" + complement_x + "(" + b + "," + a + ")"
    
    Note: For integer parameters, use binomial expansion
    If StringCore.contains(a, "integer") and StringCore.contains(b, "integer"):
        Return "Σ C(" + a + "+" + b + "-1,k) * " + x + "^(" + a + "+k) * (1-" + x + ")^(" + b + "-1-k)"
    
    Note: General case - regularized incomplete beta function
    Return "I_" + x + "(" + a + "," + b + ")"

Process called "polygamma_function" that takes order as Integer, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Polygamma function ψ^(n)(z) - nth derivative of digamma
    Note: Handle special cases based on order
    If order equals 0:
        Note: Digamma function ψ(z) = d/dz ln(Γ(z))
        If argument equals "1":
            Return "-γ"
        If argument equals "2":
            Return "1 - γ"
        If argument equals "1/2":
            Return "-γ - 2*ln(2)"
        Return "ψ(" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals 1:
        Note: Trigamma function ψ'(z)
        If argument equals "1":
            Return "π²/6"
        If argument equals "1/2":
            Return "π²/2"
        Return "ψ'(" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals 2:
        Note: Tetragamma function ψ''(z)
        If argument equals "1":
            Return "-2*ζ(3)"
        Return "ψ''(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case - use series representation
    If order > 0:
        Let sign be if (order % 2 equals 0) then "" else "-"
        Return sign + "(" + Integer.toString(order) + "!) * ζ(" + Integer.toString(order + 1) + "," + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Invalid order
    Return "ψ^(" + Integer.toString(order) + ")(" + argument + ")"

Note: =====================================================================
Note: ERROR FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "error_function" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Error function erf(x) = (2/√π)∫₀ˣ e^(-t²) dt
    Note: Handle special values and series representation
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "∞":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "-∞":
        Return "-1"
    
    Note: Odd function property: erf(-x) = -erf(x)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return "-erf(" + positive_arg + ")"
    
    Note: Special rational values
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "erf(1) ≈ 0.8427"
    
    If argument equals "2":
        Return "erf(2) ≈ 0.9953"
    
    Note: Use series expansion for small values: erf(x) = (2/√π) * Σ ((-1)^n * x^(2n+1)) / (n! * (2n+1))
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "small"):
        Return "(2/√π) * (" + argument + " - " + argument + "³/3 + " + argument + "⁵/10 - ...)"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "erf(" + argument + ")"

Process called "complementary_error_function" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Complementary error function erfc(x) = 1 - erf(x)
    Note: Handle special values using relationship with error function
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "∞":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "-∞":
        Return "2"
    
    Note: Use relationship: erfc(x) = 1 - erf(x)
    If argument equals "x":
        Return "1 - erf(x)"
    
    Note: For negative arguments: erfc(-x) = 2 - erfc(x)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return "2 - erfc(" + positive_arg + ")"
    
    Note: Special values
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "erfc(1) ≈ 0.1573"
    
    If argument equals "2":
        Return "erfc(2) ≈ 0.0047"
    
    Note: Use asymptotic expansion for large arguments: erfc(x) ~ (e^(-x²))/(x*√π) * (1 - 1/(2x²) + ...)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        Return "(exp(-" + argument + "²))/(" + argument + "*√π) * (1 - 1/(2*" + argument + "²) + ...)"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "erfc(" + argument + ")"

Process called "scaled_complementary_error_function" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Scaled complementary error function erfcx(x) = e^(x²)erfc(x)
    Note: Handle special values and asymptotic behavior
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If argument equals "∞":
        Return "0"
    
    Note: Use definition: erfcx(x) = exp(x²) * erfc(x)
    If argument equals "x":
        Return "exp(x²) * erfc(x)"
    
    Note: For large arguments, use asymptotic expansion: erfcx(x) ~ 1/(x*√π) * (1 - 1/(2x²) + 3/(4x⁴) - ...)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        Return "1/(" + argument + "*√π) * (1 - 1/(2*" + argument + "²) + 3/(4*" + argument + "⁴) - ...)"
    
    Note: For small arguments, use series: erfcx(x) = 1 - (2/√π)*x + ...
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "small"):
        Return "1 - (2/√π)*" + argument + " + ..."
    
    Note: General case
    Return "erfcx(" + argument + ")"

Process called "imaginary_error_function" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Imaginary error function erfi(x) = -i·erf(ix)
    Note: Handle special values and series representation
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "∞":
        Return "∞"
    
    If argument equals "-∞":
        Return "-∞"
    
    Note: Use definition: erfi(x) = -i * erf(i*x)
    If argument equals "x":
        Return "-i * erf(i*x)"
    
    Note: Real function with odd symmetry: erfi(-x) = -erfi(x)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Return "-erfi(" + positive_arg + ")"
    
    Note: Series representation: erfi(x) = (2/√π) * Σ (x^(2n+1)) / (n! * (2n+1))
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "series"):
        Return "(2/√π) * (" + argument + " + " + argument + "³/3 + " + argument + "⁵/10 + ...)"
    
    Note: Relationship with Dawson function: erfi(x) = (2/√π) * exp(x²) * D(x)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "dawson"):
        Return "(2/√π) * exp(" + argument + "²) * D(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "erfi(" + argument + ")"

Process called "fresnel_integrals" that takes argument as String returns Dictionary[String, String]:
    Note: Fresnel integrals S(x) and C(x)
    Note: Handle special values and series representations
    Let result be Dictionary.empty()
    
    If argument equals "0":
        Dictionary.set(result, "S", "0")
        Dictionary.set(result, "C", "0")
        Return result
    
    If argument equals "∞":
        Dictionary.set(result, "S", "1/2")
        Dictionary.set(result, "C", "1/2")
        Return result
    
    If argument equals "-∞":
        Dictionary.set(result, "S", "-1/2")
        Dictionary.set(result, "C", "-1/2")
        Return result
    
    Note: Odd function property for S(x), even for C(x)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-"):
        Let positive_arg be StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument))
        Dictionary.set(result, "S", "-S(" + positive_arg + ")")
        Dictionary.set(result, "C", "-C(" + positive_arg + ")")
        Return result
    
    Note: Series representations
    Note: S(x) = ∫₀ˣ sin(πt²/2) dt = Σ ((-1)^n * (π/2)^(2n+1) * x^(4n+3)) / ((2n+1)! * (4n+3))
    Note: C(x) = ∫₀ˣ cos(πt²/2) dt = Σ ((-1)^n * (π/2)^(2n) * x^(4n+1)) / ((2n)! * (4n+1))
    
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "series"):
        Dictionary.set(result, "S", "Σ ((-1)^n * (π/2)^(2n+1) * " + argument + "^(4n+3)) / ((2n+1)! * (4n+3))")
        Dictionary.set(result, "C", "Σ ((-1)^n * (π/2)^(2n) * " + argument + "^(4n+1)) / ((2n)! * (4n+1))")
        Return result
    
    Note: General case
    Dictionary.set(result, "S", "S(" + argument + ")")
    Dictionary.set(result, "C", "C(" + argument + ")")
    Return result

Note: =====================================================================
Note: BESSEL FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "bessel_j" that takes order as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Bessel function of the first kind J_ν(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and series representation
    If argument equals "0":
        If order equals "0":
            Return "1"
        Otherwise:
            Return "0"
    
    Note: Integer order special cases
    If order equals "0" and argument equals "x":
        Return "J_0(x) = Σ ((-1)^n / (n!)^2) * (x/2)^(2n)"
    
    If order equals "1" and argument equals "x":
        Return "J_1(x) = (x/2) * Σ ((-1)^n / (n!(n+1)!)) * (x/2)^(2n)"
    
    If order equals "1/2":
        Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * sin(" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals "-1/2":
        Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * cos(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Negative order: J_{-n}(x) = (-1)^n * J_n(x) for integer n
    If StringCore.starts_with(order, "-"):
        Let positive_order be StringCore.substring(order, 1, StringCore.length(order))
        Return "(-1)^" + positive_order + " * J_" + positive_order + "(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Large argument asymptotics: J_ν(x) ~ √(2/(πx)) * cos(x - πν/2 - π/4)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * cos(" + argument + " - π*" + order + "/2 - π/4)"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "J_" + order + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "bessel_y" that takes order as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Bessel function of the second kind Y_ν(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and asymptotic behavior
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "-∞"
    
    Note: Half-integer orders
    If order equals "1/2":
        Return "-√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * cos(" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals "-1/2":
        Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * sin(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Integer order special cases
    If order equals "0":
        Return "Y_0(" + argument + ") = (2/π) * [ln(" + argument + "/2) + γ] * J_0(" + argument + ") + ..."
    
    If order equals "1":
        Return "Y_1(" + argument + ") = (2/π) * [(ln(" + argument + "/2) + γ) * J_1(" + argument + ") - 1/" + argument + " + ...]"
    
    Note: Negative order: Y_{-n}(x) = (-1)^n * Y_n(x) for integer n
    If StringCore.starts_with(order, "-"):
        Let positive_order be StringCore.substring(order, 1, StringCore.length(order))
        Return "(-1)^" + positive_order + " * Y_" + positive_order + "(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Large argument asymptotics: Y_ν(x) ~ √(2/(πx)) * sin(x - πν/2 - π/4)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * sin(" + argument + " - π*" + order + "/2 - π/4)"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "Y_" + order + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "modified_bessel_i" that takes order as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Modified Bessel function of the first kind I_ν(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and series representation
    If argument equals "0":
        If order equals "0":
            Return "1"
        Otherwise:
            Return "0"
    
    Note: Relationship with regular Bessel: I_ν(x) = i^(-ν) * J_ν(ix)
    If order equals "0":
        Return "I_0(" + argument + ") = Σ (1/(n!)^2) * (" + argument + "/2)^(2n)"
    
    If order equals "1":
        Return "I_1(" + argument + ") = (" + argument + "/2) * Σ (1/(n!(n+1)!)) * (" + argument + "/2)^(2n)"
    
    Note: Half-integer orders
    If order equals "1/2":
        Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * sinh(" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals "-1/2":
        Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * cosh(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Large argument asymptotics: I_ν(x) ~ (e^x)/√(2πx) * (1 - (4ν^2-1)/(8x) + ...)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        Return "exp(" + argument + ")/√(2π*" + argument + ") * (1 - (4*" + order + "^2-1)/(8*" + argument + ") + ...)"
    
    Note: Negative order: I_{-ν}(x) = I_ν(x) + (2/π)*sin(πν)*K_ν(x)
    If StringCore.starts_with(order, "-"):
        Let positive_order be StringCore.substring(order, 1, StringCore.length(order))
        Return "I_" + positive_order + "(" + argument + ") + (2/π)*sin(π*" + positive_order + ")*K_" + positive_order + "(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "I_" + order + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "modified_bessel_k" that takes order as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Modified Bessel function of the second kind K_ν(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and asymptotic behavior
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "+∞"
    
    If argument equals "∞":
        Return "0"
    
    Note: Half-integer orders
    If order equals "1/2":
        Return "√(π/(2*" + argument + ")) * exp(-" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals "-1/2":
        Return "√(π/(2*" + argument + ")) * exp(-" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Integer order special cases
    If order equals "0":
        Return "K_0(" + argument + ") = -[ln(" + argument + "/2) + γ] * I_0(" + argument + ") + ..."
    
    If order equals "1":
        Return "K_1(" + argument + ") = (1/" + argument + ") + [ln(" + argument + "/2) - γ] * I_1(" + argument + ") + ..."
    
    Note: Symmetry property: K_{-ν}(x) = K_ν(x)
    If StringCore.starts_with(order, "-"):
        Let positive_order be StringCore.substring(order, 1, StringCore.length(order))
        Return "K_" + positive_order + "(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Large argument asymptotics: K_ν(x) ~ √(π/(2x)) * e^(-x) * (1 + (4ν^2-1)/(8x) + ...)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        Return "√(π/(2*" + argument + ")) * exp(-" + argument + ") * (1 + (4*" + order + "^2-1)/(8*" + argument + ") + ...)"
    
    Note: Small argument behavior for K_0: K_0(x) ~ -ln(x) as x -> 0
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "small") and order equals "0":
        Return "-ln(" + argument + ") + O(" + argument + "^2*ln(" + argument + "))"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "K_" + order + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "hankel_functions" that takes kind as Integer, order as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Hankel functions H^(1)_ν(x) and H^(2)_ν(x)
    Note: Handle first and second kind Hankel functions
    If kind equals 1:
        Note: H^(1)_ν(x) = J_ν(x) + i*Y_ν(x)
        Return "J_" + order + "(" + argument + ") + i*Y_" + order + "(" + argument + ")"
    
    If kind equals 2:
        Note: H^(2)_ν(x) = J_ν(x) - i*Y_ν(x)
        Return "J_" + order + "(" + argument + ") - i*Y_" + order + "(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Special case at argument = 0
    If argument equals "0":
        If order equals "0":
            If kind equals 1:
                Return "1 - i*∞"
            Otherwise:
                Return "1 + i*∞"
        Otherwise:
            Return "-i*∞"
    
    Note: Large argument asymptotics
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        If kind equals 1:
            Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * exp(i*(" + argument + " - π*" + order + "/2 - π/4))"
        Otherwise:
            Return "√(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * exp(-i*(" + argument + " - π*" + order + "/2 - π/4))"
    
    Note: Wronskian relation: H^(1)_ν * H^(2)_ν' - H^(1)_ν' * H^(2)_ν = -4i/(πx)
    
    Note: Invalid kind
    If kind != 1 and kind != 2:
        Return "Invalid Hankel function kind: " + Integer.toString(kind)
    
    Note: General case
    Return "H^(" + Integer.toString(kind) + ")_" + order + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "spherical_bessel" that takes order as Integer, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Spherical Bessel functions j_n(x), y_n(x)
    Note: Handle spherical Bessel functions of first kind j_n(x)
    If argument equals "0":
        If order equals 0:
            Return "1"
        Otherwise:
            Return "0"
    
    Note: Relationship with regular Bessel: j_n(x) = √(π/(2x)) * J_{n+1/2}(x)
    If order equals 0:
        Return "sin(" + argument + ")/" + argument
    
    If order equals 1:
        Return "sin(" + argument + ")/" + argument + "^2 - cos(" + argument + ")/" + argument
    
    If order equals 2:
        Return "(3/" + argument + "^3 - 1/" + argument + ")*sin(" + argument + ") - (3/" + argument + "^2)*cos(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General recursion relation: j_{n+1}(x) = (2n+1)/x * j_n(x) - j_{n-1}(x)
    If order > 2:
        Return "j_" + Integer.toString(order) + "(" + argument + ") [use recursion relation]"
    
    Note: Large argument asymptotics: j_n(x) ~ (1/x) * sin(x - nπ/2)
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "large"):
        Return "(1/" + argument + ") * sin(" + argument + " - " + Integer.toString(order) + "*π/2)"
    
    Note: Small argument behavior: j_n(x) ~ x^n / (2n+1)!!
    If StringCore.contains(argument, "small"):
        Return argument + "^" + Integer.toString(order) + " / (" + Integer.toString(2*order + 1) + "!!)"
    
    Note: Spherical Neumann functions y_n(x) (second kind)
    Note: y_0(x) = -cos(x)/x, y_1(x) = -cos(x)/x^2 - sin(x)/x
    
    Note: General case
    Return "j_" + Integer.toString(order) + "(" + argument + ")"

Note: =====================================================================
Note: ORTHOGONAL POLYNOMIAL OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "legendre_polynomial" that takes degree as Integer, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Legendre polynomial P_n(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and low-degree polynomials
    If degree equals 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If degree equals 1:
        Return argument
    
    If degree equals 2:
        Return "(3*" + argument + "²-1)/2"
    
    If degree equals 3:
        Return "(5*" + argument + "³-3*" + argument + ")/2"
    
    If degree equals 4:
        Return "(35*" + argument + "⁴-30*" + argument + "²+3)/8"
    
    If degree equals 5:
        Return "(63*" + argument + "⁵-70*" + argument + "³+15*" + argument + ")/8"
    
    Note: General case using recursive formula
    Return "P_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "associated_legendre" that takes degree as Integer, order as Integer, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Associated Legendre polynomial P_n^m(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and low-degree associated polynomials
    If order equals 0:
        Return legendre_polynomial(degree, argument)
    
    If degree equals 1 and order equals 1:
        Return "sqrt(1-" + argument + "²)"
    
    If degree equals 2 and order equals 1:
        Return "3*" + argument + "*sqrt(1-" + argument + "²)"
    
    If degree equals 2 and order equals 2:
        Return "3*(1-" + argument + "²)"
    
    If degree equals 3 and order equals 1:
        Return "(3/2)*sqrt(1-" + argument + "²)*(5*" + argument + "²-1)"
    
    If degree equals 3 and order equals 2:
        Return "15*" + argument + "*(1-" + argument + "²)"
    
    If degree equals 3 and order equals 3:
        Return "15*sqrt(1-" + argument + "²)³"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "P_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "^" + Integer.toString(order) + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "chebyshev_first_kind" that takes degree as Integer, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind T_n(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and low-degree Chebyshev polynomials
    If degree equals 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If degree equals 1:
        Return argument
    
    If degree equals 2:
        Return "2*" + argument + "²-1"
    
    If degree equals 3:
        Return "4*" + argument + "³-3*" + argument
    
    If degree equals 4:
        Return "8*" + argument + "⁴-8*" + argument + "²+1"
    
    If degree equals 5:
        Return "16*" + argument + "⁵-20*" + argument + "³+5*" + argument
    
    If degree equals 6:
        Return "32*" + argument + "⁶-48*" + argument + "⁴+18*" + argument + "²-1"
    
    Note: General case using trigonometric identity T_n(cos θ) = cos(nθ)
    Return "T_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "chebyshev_second_kind" that takes degree as Integer, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Chebyshev polynomial of the second kind U_n(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and low-degree Chebyshev second kind polynomials
    If degree equals 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If degree equals 1:
        Return "2*" + argument
    
    If degree equals 2:
        Return "4*" + argument + "²-1"
    
    If degree equals 3:
        Return "8*" + argument + "³-4*" + argument
    
    If degree equals 4:
        Return "16*" + argument + "⁴-12*" + argument + "²+1"
    
    If degree equals 5:
        Return "32*" + argument + "⁵-32*" + argument + "³+6*" + argument
    
    Note: General case using trigonometric identity U_n(cos θ) = sin((n+1)θ)/sin θ
    Return "U_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "hermite_polynomial" that takes degree as Integer, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Hermite polynomial H_n(x) (physicist's version)
    Note: Handle special cases and low-degree Hermite polynomials
    If degree equals 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If degree equals 1:
        Return "2*" + argument
    
    If degree equals 2:
        Return "4*" + argument + "²-2"
    
    If degree equals 3:
        Return "8*" + argument + "³-12*" + argument
    
    If degree equals 4:
        Return "16*" + argument + "⁴-48*" + argument + "²+12"
    
    If degree equals 5:
        Return "32*" + argument + "⁵-160*" + argument + "³+120*" + argument
    
    If degree equals 6:
        Return "64*" + argument + "⁶-480*" + argument + "⁴+720*" + argument + "²-120"
    
    Note: General case using recurrence relation H_{n+1}(x) = 2x*H_n(x) - 2n*H_{n-1}(x)
    Return "H_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "laguerre_polynomial" that takes degree as Integer, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Laguerre polynomial L_n(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and low-degree Laguerre polynomials
    If degree equals 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If degree equals 1:
        Return "1-" + argument
    
    If degree equals 2:
        Return "(" + argument + "²-4*" + argument + "+2)/2"
    
    If degree equals 3:
        Return "(-" + argument + "³+9*" + argument + "²-18*" + argument + "+6)/6"
    
    If degree equals 4:
        Return "(" + argument + "⁴-16*" + argument + "³+72*" + argument + "²-96*" + argument + "+24)/24"
    
    If degree equals 5:
        Return "(-" + argument + "⁵+25*" + argument + "⁴-200*" + argument + "³+600*" + argument + "²-600*" + argument + "+120)/120"
    
    Note: General case using recurrence relation (n+1)*L_{n+1}(x) = (2n+1-x)*L_n(x) - n*L_{n-1}(x)
    Return "L_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "jacobi_polynomial" that takes degree as Integer, alpha as String, beta as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Jacobi polynomial P_n^(α,β)(x)
    Note: Handle special cases and low-degree Jacobi polynomials
    If degree equals 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If degree equals 1:
        Return "(" + alpha + "+" + beta + "+2)*" + argument + "/2 + (" + alpha + "-" + beta + ")/2"
    
    Note: Special case when α = β = 0 (Legendre polynomials)
    If alpha equals "0" and beta equals "0":
        Return legendre_polynomial(degree, argument)
    
    Note: Special case when α = β = 1/2 (Chebyshev first kind)
    If alpha equals "1/2" and beta equals "1/2":
        Let coefficient be "2^(1-" + Integer.toString(degree) + ")"
        Return coefficient + "*T_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: Special case when α = β = -1/2 (Chebyshev second kind with scaling)
    If alpha equals "-1/2" and beta equals "-1/2":
        Return "U_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "(" + argument + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "P_" + Integer.toString(degree) + "^(" + alpha + "," + beta + ")(" + argument + ")"

Note: =====================================================================
Note: HYPERGEOMETRIC FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "hypergeometric_1f1" that takes a as String, b as String, z as String returns String:
    Note: Confluent hypergeometric function ₁F₁(a;b;z)
    Note: Handle special cases and identities
    If z equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If a equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If a equals "1" and b equals "1":
        Return "exp(" + z + ")"
    
    If a equals "1" and b equals "2":
        Return "(exp(" + z + ")-1)/" + z
    
    If a equals "1/2" and b equals "3/2":
        Return "sinh(" + z + ")/" + z
    
    If a equals "1/2" and b equals "1/2":
        Return "exp(" + z + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative integer b (function undefined)
    If StringCore.starts_with(b, "-") and StringCore.contains(b, ".") equals false:
        Return "undefined"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "₁F₁(" + a + ";" + b + ";" + z + ")"

Process called "hypergeometric_2f1" that takes a as String, b as String, c as String, z as String returns String:
    Note: Gaussian hypergeometric function ₂F₁(a,b;c;z)
    Note: Handle special cases and identities
    If z equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If a equals "0" or b equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If z equals "1":
        Note: ₂F₁(a,b;c;1) = Γ(c)Γ(c-a-b)/(Γ(c-a)Γ(c-b))
        Return "Γ(" + c + ")Γ(" + c + "-" + a + "-" + b + ")/(Γ(" + c + "-" + a + ")Γ(" + c + "-" + b + "))"
    
    If a equals "1" and b equals "1" and c equals "2":
        Return "-log(1-" + z + ")/" + z
    
    If a equals "1/2" and b equals "1/2" and c equals "3/2":
        Return "arcsin(" + z + ")/" + z
    
    If a equals "1/2" and b equals "1/2" and c equals "1":
        Return "1/sqrt(1-" + z + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative integer c (function undefined)
    If StringCore.starts_with(c, "-") and StringCore.contains(c, ".") equals false:
        Return "undefined"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "₂F₁(" + a + "," + b + ";" + c + ";" + z + ")"

Process called "hypergeometric_0f1" that takes b as String, z as String returns String:
    Note: Hypergeometric function ₀F₁(;b;z)
    Note: Handle special cases and identities
    If z equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If b equals "1":
        Return "sinh(" + z + ")/" + z
    
    If b equals "2":
        Return "(cosh(" + z + ")-1)/" + z
    
    If b equals "1/2":
        Return "cosh(2*sqrt(" + z + "))"
    
    If b equals "3/2":
        Return "sinh(2*sqrt(" + z + "))/(2*sqrt(" + z + "))"
    
    Note: Relation to Bessel functions: ₀F₁(;b;z) = Γ(b)(z/4)^((1-b)/2) * I_{b-1}(2*sqrt(z))
    If b equals "1":
        Return "I_0(2*sqrt(" + z + "))"
    
    Note: Handle negative integer b (function undefined)
    If StringCore.starts_with(b, "-") and StringCore.contains(b, ".") equals false:
        Return "undefined"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "₀F₁(;" + b + ";" + z + ")"

Process called "hypergeometric_pfq" that takes p_params as List[String], q_params as List[String], z as String returns String:
    Note: Generalized hypergeometric function ₚFᵩ
    Note: Handle special cases and construct general form
    If z equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    Let p_count be List.length(p_params)
    Let q_count be List.length(q_params)
    
    Note: Handle degenerate cases
    If p_count equals 0 and q_count equals 0:
        Return "exp(" + z + ")"
    
    If p_count equals 0 and q_count equals 1:
        Return hypergeometric_0f1(List.get(q_params, 0), z)
    
    If p_count equals 1 and q_count equals 1:
        Return hypergeometric_1f1(List.get(p_params, 0), List.get(q_params, 0), z)
    
    If p_count equals 2 and q_count equals 1:
        Return hypergeometric_2f1(List.get(p_params, 0), List.get(p_params, 1), List.get(q_params, 0), z)
    
    Note: Build parameter string for general case
    Let p_str be StringCore.join(p_params, ",")
    Let q_str be StringCore.join(q_params, ",")
    
    Return "₍" + Integer.toString(p_count) + "₎F₍" + Integer.toString(q_count) + "₎(" + p_str + ";" + q_str + ";" + z + ")"

Process called "hypergeometric_transformations" that takes function as HypergeometricFunction, transformation_type as String returns String:
    Note: Apply transformation formulas to hypergeometric functions
    Note: Handle various transformation types for hypergeometric functions
    
    If transformation_type equals "linear":
        Note: Linear transformation z → az
        Return "Apply linear transformation to " + HypergeometricFunction.toString(function)
    
    If transformation_type equals "quadratic":
        Note: Quadratic transformation using Pfaff transformations
        Return "Apply quadratic transformation to " + HypergeometricFunction.toString(function)
    
    If transformation_type equals "euler":
        Note: Euler transformation z → z/(z-1)
        Return "Apply Euler transformation to " + HypergeometricFunction.toString(function)
    
    If transformation_type equals "pfaff":
        Note: Pfaff transformation (1-z)^(-a)₂F₁(a,c-b;c;z/(z-1))
        Return "Apply Pfaff transformation to " + HypergeometricFunction.toString(function)
    
    If transformation_type equals "kummer":
        Note: Kummer transformation for confluent functions
        Return "Apply Kummer transformation to " + HypergeometricFunction.toString(function)
    
    If transformation_type equals "bailey":
        Note: Bailey transformation for balanced hypergeometric functions
        Return "Apply Bailey transformation to " + HypergeometricFunction.toString(function)
    
    Note: General transformation case
    Return "Apply " + transformation_type + " transformation to " + HypergeometricFunction.toString(function)

Note: =====================================================================
Note: ELLIPTIC FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "elliptic_integral_first_kind" that takes phi as String, modulus as String returns String:
    Note: Elliptic integral of the first kind F(φ,k)
    Note: Handle special cases and standard forms
    If phi equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If modulus equals "0":
        Return phi
    
    If modulus equals "1":
        Return "ln(tan(π/4 + " + phi + "/2))"
    
    If phi equals "π/2":
        Note: Complete elliptic integral K(k)
        Return "K(" + modulus + ")"
    
    If phi equals "π":
        Return "2*K(" + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative phi (odd function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(phi, "-"):
        Let positive_phi be StringCore.substring(phi, 1, StringCore.length(phi))
        Return "-" + elliptic_integral_first_kind(positive_phi, modulus)
    
    Note: General case
    Return "F(" + phi + "," + modulus + ")"

Process called "elliptic_integral_second_kind" that takes phi as String, modulus as String returns String:
    Note: Elliptic integral of the second kind E(φ,k)
    Note: Handle special cases and standard forms
    If phi equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If modulus equals "0":
        Return phi
    
    If modulus equals "1":
        Return "sin(" + phi + ")"
    
    If phi equals "π/2":
        Note: Complete elliptic integral E(k)
        Return "E(" + modulus + ")"
    
    If phi equals "π":
        Return "2*E(" + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative phi (odd function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(phi, "-"):
        Let positive_phi be StringCore.substring(phi, 1, StringCore.length(phi))
        Return "-" + elliptic_integral_second_kind(positive_phi, modulus)
    
    Note: General case
    Return "E(" + phi + "," + modulus + ")"

Process called "elliptic_integral_third_kind" that takes phi as String, n as String, modulus as String returns String:
    Note: Elliptic integral of the third kind Π(n;φ,k)
    Note: Handle special cases and parameter restrictions
    If phi equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If n equals "0":
        Return elliptic_integral_first_kind(phi, modulus)
    
    If modulus equals "0":
        Return "arctan(sqrt(" + n + ")*tan(" + phi + "))/sqrt(" + n + ")"
    
    If n equals "1":
        Note: Singular case, integral diverges at sin²φ = 1
        If phi equals "π/2":
            Return "infinity"
        Return "Π(1;" + phi + "," + modulus + ")"
    
    If phi equals "π/2":
        Note: Complete elliptic integral of third kind
        Return "Π(" + n + "," + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative phi (odd function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(phi, "-"):
        Let positive_phi be StringCore.substring(phi, 1, StringCore.length(phi))
        Return "-" + elliptic_integral_third_kind(positive_phi, n, modulus)
    
    Note: General case
    Return "Π(" + n + ";" + phi + "," + modulus + ")"

Process called "jacobi_elliptic_sn" that takes u as String, modulus as String returns String:
    Note: Jacobi elliptic function sn(u,k)
    Note: Handle special cases and modulus limits
    If u equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If modulus equals "0":
        Return "sin(" + u + ")"
    
    If modulus equals "1":
        Return "tanh(" + u + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative u (odd function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(u, "-"):
        Let positive_u be StringCore.substring(u, 1, StringCore.length(u))
        Return "-sn(" + positive_u + "," + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: Period 4K(k) where K is complete elliptic integral
    Let period be "4*K(" + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "sn(" + u + "," + modulus + ")"

Process called "jacobi_elliptic_cn" that takes u as String, modulus as String returns String:
    Note: Jacobi elliptic function cn(u,k)
    Note: Handle special cases and modulus limits
    If u equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If modulus equals "0":
        Return "cos(" + u + ")"
    
    If modulus equals "1":
        Return "sech(" + u + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative u (even function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(u, "-"):
        Let positive_u be StringCore.substring(u, 1, StringCore.length(u))
        Return "cn(" + positive_u + "," + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: Period 4K(k)
    Let period be "4*K(" + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: Identity: cn²(u,k) + sn²(u,k) = 1
    Note: General case
    Return "cn(" + u + "," + modulus + ")"

Process called "jacobi_elliptic_dn" that takes u as String, modulus as String returns String:
    Note: Jacobi elliptic function dn(u,k)
    Note: Handle special cases and modulus limits
    If u equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If modulus equals "0":
        Return "1"
    
    If modulus equals "1":
        Return "sech(" + u + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative u (even function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(u, "-"):
        Let positive_u be StringCore.substring(u, 1, StringCore.length(u))
        Return "dn(" + positive_u + "," + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: Period 2K(k)
    Let period be "2*K(" + modulus + ")"
    
    Note: Identity: dn²(u,k) + k²*sn²(u,k) = 1
    Note: General case
    Return "dn(" + u + "," + modulus + ")"

Process called "weierstrass_p" that takes z as String, invariants as Dictionary[String, String] returns String:
    Note: Weierstrass elliptic function ℘(z;g₂,g₃)
    Note: Handle special cases and invariant conditions
    If z equals "0":
        Return "infinity"
    
    Let g2 be Dictionary.get(invariants, "g2")
    Let g3 be Dictionary.get(invariants, "g3")
    
    Note: Handle degenerate cases
    Let discriminant be "" + g2 + "³-27*" + g3 + "²"
    If discriminant equals "0":
        Return "degenerate_case"
    
    Note: Special case: equianharmonic (g2=0)
    If g2 equals "0":
        Note: ℘(z) has period ω where ω³ = g3/4
        Return "℘_equi(" + z + ";" + g3 + ")"
    
    Note: Special case: lemniscatic (g3=0)
    If g3 equals "0":
        Note: ℘(z) has real periods
        Return "℘_lemn(" + z + ";" + g2 + ")"
    
    Note: Handle negative z (even function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(z, "-"):
        Let positive_z be StringCore.substring(z, 1, StringCore.length(z))
        Return "℘(" + positive_z + ";" + g2 + "," + g3 + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "℘(" + z + ";" + g2 + "," + g3 + ")"

Note: =====================================================================
Note: ZETA AND L-FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "riemann_zeta" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Riemann zeta function ζ(s)
    Note: Handle special values and known results
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "infinity"
    
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "-1/2"
    
    If argument equals "-1":
        Return "-1/12"
    
    If argument equals "2":
        Return "π²/6"
    
    If argument equals "3":
        Return "Apéry's_constant"
    
    If argument equals "4":
        Return "π⁴/90"
    
    If argument equals "6":
        Return "π⁶/945"
    
    If argument equals "8":
        Return "π⁸/9450"
    
    Note: Handle negative even integers
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-") and StringCore.contains(argument, ".") equals false:
        Let n be Integer.parse(StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument)))
        If n mod 2 equals 0:
            Return "0"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "ζ(" + argument + ")"

Process called "hurwitz_zeta" that takes s as String, a as String returns String:
    Note: Hurwitz zeta function ζ(s,a)
    Note: Handle special cases and reduction to Riemann zeta
    If a equals "1":
        Return riemann_zeta(s)
    
    If s equals "1":
        Note: Harmonic series diverges
        Return "infinity"
    
    If s equals "0":
        Return "1/2 - " + a
    
    If s equals "-1":
        Return "(" + a + "² - " + a + " + 1/6)/2"
    
    If s equals "2" and a equals "1/2":
        Return "π²/6 * (4 - π²/3)"
    
    If s equals "2" and a equals "1/4":
        Return "π²/2 + 8*G"
    
    Note: Handle rational a with simple forms
    If a equals "1/2":
        Return "(2^" + s + " - 1) * ζ(" + s + ")"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "ζ(" + s + "," + a + ")"

Process called "dirichlet_eta" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Dirichlet eta function η(s) = (1-2^(1-s))ζ(s)
    Note: Handle special values and relationship to zeta function
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "ln(2)"
    
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "1/2"
    
    If argument equals "2":
        Return "π²/12"
    
    If argument equals "3":
        Return "3*ζ(3)/4"
    
    If argument equals "4":
        Return "7*π⁴/720"
    
    Note: Handle negative integers - eta continues analytically where zeta has poles
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-") and StringCore.contains(argument, ".") equals false:
        Let n be Integer.parse(StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument)))
        If n equals 1:
            Return "1/4"
        If n equals 3:
            Return "-1/8"
    
    Note: General case using relationship to zeta
    Return "(1 - 2^(1-" + argument + ")) * ζ(" + argument + ")"

Process called "dirichlet_beta" that takes argument as String returns String:
    Note: Dirichlet beta function β(s) = Σ((-1)^n/(2n+1)^s)
    Note: Handle special values and known results
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "1/2"
    
    If argument equals "1":
        Return "π/4"
    
    If argument equals "2":
        Return "G" Note: Catalan's constant
    
    If argument equals "3":
        Return "π³/32"
    
    If argument equals "4":
        Return "β(4)"
    
    If argument equals "5":
        Return "5*π⁵/1536"
    
    Note: Handle negative odd integers (zeros of beta function)
    If StringCore.starts_with(argument, "-") and StringCore.contains(argument, ".") equals false:
        Let n be Integer.parse(StringCore.substring(argument, 1, StringCore.length(argument)))
        If n mod 2 equals 1:
            Return "0"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "β(" + argument + ")"

Process called "polylogarithm" that takes order as String, argument as String returns String:
    Note: Polylogarithm function Li_s(z) = Σ(z^n/n^s)
    Note: Handle special cases and known values
    If argument equals "0":
        Return "0"
    
    If argument equals "1":
        If order equals "1":
            Return "-ln(1-1)"
        Return "ζ(" + order + ")"
    
    If argument equals "-1":
        Return "-η(" + order + ")"
    
    If order equals "1":
        Return "-ln(1-" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals "2":
        Note: Dilogarithm - special function
        If argument equals "1/2":
            Return "π²/12 - (ln(2))²/2"
        If argument equals "-1":
            Return "-π²/12"
        Return "Li_2(" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals "0":
        Return argument + "/(1-" + argument + ")"
    
    If order equals "-1":
        Return argument + "/(1-" + argument + ")²"
    
    Note: Handle integer orders with special properties
    If order equals "3" and argument equals "1/2":
        Return "7*ζ(3)/8 - π²*ln(2)/12 + (ln(2))³/6"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "Li_" + order + "(" + argument + ")"

Note: =====================================================================
Note: STATISTICAL FUNCTION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "normal_distribution_cdf" that takes x as String, mean as String, variance as String returns String:
    Note: Cumulative distribution function of normal distribution
    Note: Φ((x-μ)/σ) where Φ is standard normal CDF
    
    If mean equals "0" and variance equals "1":
        Note: Standard normal distribution
        If x equals "0":
            Return "1/2"
        Return "(1 + erf(" + x + "/√2))/2"
    
    Let sigma be "sqrt(" + variance + ")"
    Let standardized be "(" + x + " - " + mean + ")/" + sigma
    
    Note: Special values
    If x equals mean:
        Return "1/2"
    
    Note: Handle infinity cases
    If x equals "infinity":
        Return "1"
    
    If x equals "-infinity":
        Return "0"
    
    Note: General case using error function
    Return "(1 + erf(" + standardized + "/√2))/2"

Process called "chi_squared_distribution" that takes x as String, degrees_of_freedom as String returns String:
    Note: Chi-squared distribution PDF: (1/(2^(k/2)*Γ(k/2)))*x^(k/2-1)*exp(-x/2)
    Note: Handle special cases and parameter validation
    
    If x equals "0":
        If degrees_of_freedom equals "1" or degrees_of_freedom equals "2":
            Return "infinity"
        Return "0"
    
    Let k be degrees_of_freedom
    Let normalization be "1/(2^(" + k + "/2) * Γ(" + k + "/2))"
    Let power_term be "" + x + "^(" + k + "/2 - 1)"
    Let exp_term be "exp(-" + x + "/2)"
    
    Note: Special cases for integer degrees of freedom
    If k equals "1":
        Return "exp(-" + x + "/2)/(" + x + "*√(2π))"
    
    If k equals "2":
        Return "exp(-" + x + "/2)/2"
    
    If k equals "3":
        Return "sqrt(" + x + "/2)*exp(-" + x + "/2)/(2*sqrt(π))"
    
    If k equals "4":
        Return "" + x + "*exp(-" + x + "/2)/4"
    
    Note: General case
    Return normalization + "*" + power_term + "*" + exp_term

Process called "students_t_distribution" that takes x as String, degrees_of_freedom as String returns String:
    Note: Student's t-distribution PDF: Γ((v+1)/2)/(√(vπ)*Γ(v/2))*(1+x²/v)^(-(v+1)/2)
    Note: Handle special cases and degrees of freedom
    
    Let v be degrees_of_freedom
    Let gamma_term be "Γ((" + v + "+1)/2)"
    Let normalization be gamma_term + "/(sqrt(" + v + "*π)*Γ(" + v + "/2))"
    Let power_term be "(1 + " + x + "²/" + v + ")^(-((" + v + "+1)/2))"
    
    Note: Special cases for small degrees of freedom
    If v equals "1":
        Note: Cauchy distribution
        Return "1/(π*(1+" + x + "²))"
    
    If v equals "2":
        Return "1/(2*(1+" + x + "²/2)^(3/2))"
    
    If v equals "3":
        Return "2/(3*sqrt(3)*π*(1+" + x + "²/3)²)"
    
    Note: As v → ∞, approaches standard normal
    If v equals "infinity":
        Return "exp(-" + x + "²/2)/sqrt(2π)"
    
    Note: General case
    Return normalization + "*" + power_term

Process called "f_distribution" that takes x as String, df1 as String, df2 as String returns String:
    Note: F-distribution PDF: B(d1/2,d2/2)^(-1)*(d1/d2)^(d1/2)*x^(d1/2-1)*(1+d1*x/d2)^(-(d1+d2)/2)
    Note: Handle special cases and parameter validation
    
    If x equals "0":
        If df1 equals "1" or df1 equals "2":
            Return "infinity"
        Return "0"
    
    Let d1 be df1
    Let d2 be df2
    Let beta_term be "B(" + d1 + "/2, " + d2 + "/2)"
    Let ratio_term be "(" + d1 + "/" + d2 + ")^(" + d1 + "/2)"
    Let x_power be "" + x + "^(" + d1 + "/2 - 1)"
    Let denominator be "(1 + " + d1 + "*" + x + "/" + d2 + ")^((" + d1 + "+" + d2 + ")/2)"
    
    Note: Special cases for specific degrees of freedom
    If d1 equals "1" and d2 equals "1":
        Return "1/(π*sqrt(" + x + ")*(1+" + x + ")²)"
    
    If d1 equals "2" and d2 equals "1":
        Return "1/(2*(1+2*" + x + ")^(3/2))"
    
    If d1 equals "1" and d2 equals "2":
        Return "1/(2*sqrt(" + x + ")*(1+" + x + "/2)²)"
    
    If d1 equals "2" and d2 equals "2":
        Return "1/(2*(1+" + x + ")²)"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "(1/" + beta_term + ")*" + ratio_term + "*" + x_power + "/" + denominator

Note: =====================================================================
Note: FUNCTION COMPOSITION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "compose_functions" that takes outer_function as String, inner_function as String returns String:
    Note: Compose two symbolic functions f(g(x))
    Note: Handle simple composition patterns and standard functions
    
    Note: Handle identity functions
    If outer_function equals "x":
        Return inner_function
    If inner_function equals "x":
        Return outer_function
    
    Note: Handle constant functions
    If StringCore.contains(outer_function, "x") equals false:
        Return outer_function
    
    Note: Simple polynomial composition
    If outer_function equals "x^2" and inner_function equals "sin(x)":
        Return "sin²(x)"
    
    If outer_function equals "exp(x)" and inner_function equals "ln(x)":
        Return "x"
    
    If outer_function equals "ln(x)" and inner_function equals "exp(x)":
        Return "x"
    
    If outer_function equals "sin(x)" and inner_function equals "arcsin(x)":
        Return "x"
    
    If outer_function equals "arcsin(x)" and inner_function equals "sin(x)":
        Return "x"
    
    Note: Trigonometric compositions
    If outer_function equals "sin(x)" and inner_function equals "2*x":
        Return "sin(2*x)"
    
    Note: General composition case
    Let substituted be StringCore.replace(outer_function, "x", "(" + inner_function + ")")
    Return substituted

Process called "inverse_function" that takes function as String, variable as String returns String:
    Note: Find inverse function symbolically
    Note: Handle standard functions with known inverses
    
    Note: Elementary function inverses
    If function equals "exp(" + variable + ")":
        Return "ln(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "ln(" + variable + ")":
        Return "exp(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "" + variable + "^2":
        Return "sqrt(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "sqrt(" + variable + ")":
        Return "" + variable + "^2"
    
    Note: Trigonometric function inverses
    If function equals "sin(" + variable + ")":
        Return "arcsin(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "cos(" + variable + ")":
        Return "arccos(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "tan(" + variable + ")":
        Return "arctan(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "arcsin(" + variable + ")":
        Return "sin(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "arccos(" + variable + ")":
        Return "cos(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "arctan(" + variable + ")":
        Return "tan(" + variable + ")"
    
    Note: Hyperbolic function inverses
    If function equals "sinh(" + variable + ")":
        Return "asinh(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "cosh(" + variable + ")":
        Return "acosh(" + variable + ")"
    
    If function equals "tanh(" + variable + ")":
        Return "atanh(" + variable + ")"
    
    Note: Linear functions
    If StringCore.starts_with(function, "a*" + variable + "+b"):
        Return "(" + variable + "-b)/a"
    
    Note: General case - express as inverse
    Return "inverse(" + function + ")"

Process called "function_iteration" that takes function as String, iterations as Integer, initial_value as String returns String:
    Note: Iterate function n times: f(f(...f(x)...))
    Note: Handle iterative application of functions
    
    If iterations equals 0:
        Return initial_value
    
    If iterations equals 1:
        Return StringCore.replace(function, "x", initial_value)
    
    Note: Handle simple cases for specific functions
    If function equals "x^2":
        If iterations equals 2:
            Return "(" + initial_value + "^2)^2"
        If iterations equals 3:
            Return "((" + initial_value + "^2)^2)^2"
    
    If function equals "2*x":
        Let power be "2^" + Integer.toString(iterations)
        Return power + "*" + initial_value
    
    If function equals "x+1":
        Return initial_value + "+" + Integer.toString(iterations)
    
    If function equals "x-1":
        Return initial_value + "-" + Integer.toString(iterations)
    
    Note: Fixed point functions
    If function equals "x":
        Return initial_value
    
    Note: Handle recursive composition for general case
    Let current_value be initial_value
    Let iteration_count be 0
    While iteration_count < iterations:
        Let current_value be StringCore.replace(function, "x", current_value)
        Let iteration_count be iteration_count + 1
    
    Return "f^" + Integer.toString(iterations) + "(" + initial_value + ")"

Note: =====================================================================
Note: ASYMPTOTIC ANALYSIS OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "asymptotic_expansion_function" that takes function as SpecialFunction, expansion_point as String, order as Integer returns String:
    Note: Compute asymptotic expansion of special function
    Note: Handle common special functions and their asymptotic expansions
    
    Let function_name be SpecialFunction.getName(function)
    Let argument be SpecialFunction.getArgument(function)
    
    Note: Gamma function asymptotics (Stirling's series)
    If function_name equals "gamma" and expansion_point equals "infinity":
        If order equals 0:
            Return "sqrt(2π/" + argument + ") * (" + argument + "/e)^" + argument
        If order equals 1:
            Return "sqrt(2π/" + argument + ") * (" + argument + "/e)^" + argument + " * (1 + 1/(12*" + argument + "))"
        Return stirling_approximation(argument, order)
    
    Note: Bessel function asymptotics
    If function_name equals "bessel_j" and expansion_point equals "infinity":
        Let nu be SpecialFunction.getOrder(function)
        Return "sqrt(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * cos(" + argument + " - " + nu + "*π/2 - π/4)"
    
    If function_name equals "bessel_y" and expansion_point equals "infinity":
        Let nu be SpecialFunction.getOrder(function)
        Return "sqrt(2/(π*" + argument + ")) * sin(" + argument + " - " + nu + "*π/2 - π/4)"
    
    Note: Error function asymptotics
    If function_name equals "erf" and expansion_point equals "infinity":
        Return "1 - exp(-" + argument + "²)/(" + argument + "*sqrt(π)) * (1 - 1/(2*" + argument + "²))"
    
    Note: Exponential integral asymptotics
    If function_name equals "exponential_integral" and expansion_point equals "infinity":
        Return "exp(-" + argument + ")/" + argument + " * (1 - 1/" + argument + " + 2!/" + argument + "²)"
    
    Note: General case
    Return "asymptotic_expansion(" + SpecialFunction.toString(function) + ", " + expansion_point + ", O(" + Integer.toString(order) + "))"

Process called "stirling_approximation" that takes argument as String, order as Integer returns String:
    Note: Stirling's approximation for factorial/gamma function
    Note: Gamma(n+1) = n! ≈ sqrt(2πn) * (n/e)^n * (1 + 1/(12n) + 1/(288n²) + ...)
    
    Let base_term be "sqrt(2π*" + argument + ") * (" + argument + "/e)^" + argument
    
    If order equals 0:
        Return base_term
    
    If order equals 1:
        Return base_term + " * (1 + 1/(12*" + argument + "))"
    
    If order equals 2:
        Return base_term + " * (1 + 1/(12*" + argument + ") + 1/(288*" + argument + "²))"
    
    If order equals 3:
        Return base_term + " * (1 + 1/(12*" + argument + ") + 1/(288*" + argument + "²) - 139/(51840*" + argument + "³))"
    
    If order equals 4:
        Return base_term + " * (1 + 1/(12*" + argument + ") + 1/(288*" + argument + "²) - 139/(51840*" + argument + "³) - 571/(2488320*" + argument + "⁴))"
    
    Note: Bernoulli numbers appear in higher-order terms
    If order >= 5:
        Return base_term + " * (1 + asymptotic_series_" + Integer.toString(order) + "(" + argument + "))"
    
    Note: General case with order specified
    Return base_term + " * stirling_series_" + Integer.toString(order) + "(" + argument + ")"

Process called "saddle_point_approximation" that takes function as String, parameter as String returns String:
    Note: Saddle point method for asymptotic analysis
    Note: Find saddle points where f'(z) = 0 and approximate integral
    
    Note: Handle common integral forms that use saddle point method
    If StringCore.contains(function, "exp("):
        Note: Integrals of form ∫ exp(N*f(z)) dz for large N
        If StringCore.contains(function, parameter + "*"):
            Let saddle_point be "z_0"
            Let second_derivative be "f''(" + saddle_point + ")"
            Return "sqrt(2π/(" + parameter + "*" + second_derivative + ")) * exp(" + parameter + "*f(" + saddle_point + "))"
    
    Note: Laplace integrals ∫_0^∞ exp(-N*f(t)) g(t) dt
    If StringCore.contains(function, "exp(-" + parameter):
        Return "g(0) * sqrt(π/(2*" + parameter + "*f''(0))) * exp(-" + parameter + "*f(0))"
    
    Note: Fourier integrals ∫ exp(i*N*f(t)) g(t) dt
    If StringCore.contains(function, "exp(i*" + parameter):
        Return "sqrt(2π*i/(" + parameter + "*f''(t_0))) * g(t_0) * exp(i*" + parameter + "*f(t_0))"
    
    Note: Method of steepest descent for complex integrals
    If StringCore.contains(function, "complex"):
        Return "saddle_point_steepest_descent(" + function + ", " + parameter + ")"
    
    Note: Watson's lemma application
    If StringCore.contains(function, "t^α"):
        Return "watson_lemma_expansion(" + function + ", " + parameter + ")"
    
    Note: General saddle point approximation
    Return "saddle_point(" + function + ", " + parameter + ") ≈ dominant_contribution_at_critical_points"

Note: =====================================================================
Note: VALIDATION AND UTILITY OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "verify_function_identity" that takes function_a as String, function_b as String, variable_domain as Dictionary[String, String] returns Boolean:
    Note: Verify if two function expressions are identical
    Note: Handle various forms of function equivalence
    
    Note: Exact string match
    If function_a equals function_b:
        Return true
    
    Note: Handle trigonometric identities
    If function_a equals "sin²(x) + cos²(x)" and function_b equals "1":
        Return true
    
    If function_a equals "1 - cos²(x)" and function_b equals "sin²(x)":
        Return true
    
    If function_a equals "tan(x)" and function_b equals "sin(x)/cos(x)":
        Return true
    
    Note: Handle exponential and logarithm identities
    If function_a equals "exp(ln(x))" and function_b equals "x":
        Return true
    
    If function_a equals "ln(exp(x))" and function_b equals "x":
        Return true
    
    If function_a equals "ln(x*y)" and function_b equals "ln(x) + ln(y)":
        Return true
    
    Note: Handle algebraic identities
    If function_a equals "(x+y)²" and function_b equals "x² + 2*x*y + y²":
        Return true
    
    If function_a equals "x²-y²" and function_b equals "(x+y)*(x-y)":
        Return true
    
    Note: Handle special function identities
    If function_a equals "Γ(x+1)" and function_b equals "x*Γ(x)":
        Return true
    
    If function_a equals "erf(-x)" and function_b equals "-erf(x)":
        Return true
    
    Note: Handle hyperbolic identities
    If function_a equals "cosh²(x) - sinh²(x)" and function_b equals "1":
        Return true
    
    Note: Check domain compatibility
    Let domain_match be Dictionary.keys(variable_domain)
    
    Note: General symbolic comparison (simplified)
    Return false

Process called "function_domain_analysis" that takes function as String, variables as List[String] returns Dictionary[String, Dictionary[String, String]]:
    Note: Analyze domain and range of symbolic function
    Note: Determine natural domain and range for mathematical functions
    
    Let analysis_result be Dictionary.empty[String, Dictionary[String, String]]()
    
    For Each variable in variables:
        Let variable_analysis be Dictionary.empty[String, String]()
        
        Note: Analyze logarithmic functions
        If StringCore.contains(function, "ln(" + variable + ")") or StringCore.contains(function, "log(" + variable + ")"):
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "domain", "(0, ∞)")
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "restrictions", variable + " > 0")
        
        Note: Analyze square root functions
        If StringCore.contains(function, "sqrt(" + variable + ")"):
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "domain", "[0, ∞)")
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "restrictions", variable + " ≥ 0")
        
        Note: Analyze inverse trigonometric functions
        If StringCore.contains(function, "arcsin(" + variable + ")") or StringCore.contains(function, "arccos(" + variable + ")"):
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "domain", "[-1, 1]")
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "restrictions", "-1 ≤ " + variable + " ≤ 1")
        
        Note: Analyze inverse hyperbolic functions
        If StringCore.contains(function, "acosh(" + variable + ")"):
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "domain", "[1, ∞)")
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "restrictions", variable + " ≥ 1")
        
        If StringCore.contains(function, "atanh(" + variable + ")"):
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "domain", "(-1, 1)")
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "restrictions", "-1 < " + variable + " < 1")
        
        Note: Analyze rational functions
        If StringCore.contains(function, "/" + variable) or StringCore.contains(function, variable + "^(-"):
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "domain", "ℝ \\ {0}")
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "restrictions", variable + " ≠ 0")
        
        Note: Analyze gamma function
        If StringCore.contains(function, "Γ(" + variable + ")"):
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "domain", "ℝ \\ ℤ−")
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "restrictions", variable + " ∉ {0, -1, -2, -3, ...}")
        
        Note: Default case - real numbers
        If Dictionary.isEmpty(variable_analysis):
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "domain", "ℝ")
            Dictionary.set(variable_analysis, "restrictions", "none")
        
        Dictionary.set(analysis_result, variable, variable_analysis)
    
    Return analysis_result

Process called "benchmark_special_functions" that takes function_types as List[String], test_parameters as Dictionary[String, List[String]] returns Dictionary[String, Float]:
    Note: Benchmark performance of special function evaluations
    Note: Time evaluation performance of various special functions
    
    Let benchmark_results be Dictionary.empty[String, Float]()
    
    For Each function_type in function_types:
        Let test_params be Dictionary.get(test_parameters, function_type)
        Let total_time be 0.0
        Let test_count be List.length(test_params)
        
        Note: Benchmark gamma function
        If function_type equals "gamma":
            For Each param in test_params:
                Let start_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let result be gamma_function(param)
                Let end_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let total_time be total_time + (end_time - start_time)
        
        Note: Benchmark Bessel functions
        If function_type equals "bessel_j":
            For Each param in test_params:
                Let start_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let result be bessel_j("0", param)
                Let end_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let total_time be total_time + (end_time - start_time)
        
        Note: Benchmark error functions
        If function_type equals "erf":
            For Each param in test_params:
                Let start_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let result be error_function(param)
                Let end_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let total_time be total_time + (end_time - start_time)
        
        Note: Benchmark elliptic integrals
        If function_type equals "elliptic_k":
            For Each param in test_params:
                Let start_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let result be elliptic_integral_first_kind("π/2", param)
                Let end_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let total_time be total_time + (end_time - start_time)
        
        Note: Benchmark zeta functions
        If function_type equals "zeta":
            For Each param in test_params:
                Let start_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let result be riemann_zeta(param)
                Let end_time be SystemTime.current()
                Let total_time be total_time + (end_time - start_time)
        
        Note: Calculate average time per evaluation
        Let average_time be total_time / Float.fromInteger(test_count)
        Dictionary.set(benchmark_results, function_type, average_time)
    
    Return benchmark_results